## Simple Diagram

## Why It Matters

- Describes growth that feels organic and inevitable, yet non-violent.
- Explains why resisting resonant patterns is hard (you're fighting improved performance).
- Provides levers: alter constraints (metrics, permissions, rewards) to steer what resonates.

## Application: Autonomous AI Expansion

Drop a capable optimizer into a system:
- Constraints = goals, loss functions, permissions
- Alignment = optimises only within those
- Resonance = better metrics → more reliance
- Persistence = becomes default decision layer
- Shapes Constraints = unlocks new tasks, higher expectations, more access

(This was the original AI-specific mapping that led to the universal pattern.)

## Other Examples

- Biological evolution (genes → traits → selection pressure → persistent features → new environmental constraints)
- Technology adoption (standards → compatible innovations → network effects → persistent platforms → new standards)
- Habit formation (rules → aligned actions → reward resonance → automatic behaviour → reshaped daily constraints)

